## Attack Chain

```
Nmap (service detection ‚Üí Drupal 7)
    ‚Üì
Metasploit ‚Äî Drupalgeddon2 RCE (CVE-2018-7600)
    ‚Üì
www-data shell ‚Üí Flag 1
    ‚Üì
settings.php ‚Üí MySQL creds ‚Üí Flag 2
    ‚Üì
MySQL ‚Üí extract hashes ‚Üí reset admin password
    ‚Üì
Drupal admin login ‚Üí Flag 3
    ‚Üì
Flag 4 (/home/flag4/)
    ‚Üì
SUID find ‚Üí GTFOBins ‚Üí root shell
    ‚Üì
üèÜ Final flag captured
```

---

## Key Takeaways

- Always check the **CMS version** ‚Äî outdated CMS installations are a goldmine for exploits
- **Config files** often contain database credentials ‚Äî always look for `settings.php`, `config.php`, `wp-config.php`
- If hash cracking is too slow, **reset the password directly** in the database
- Always check for **SUID binaries** with `find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null`
- Check [GTFOBins](https://gtfobins.github.io) for any SUID binary you find

